  "prompt": "Can I keep savings account if my status changes to NRI? What happens to my PPF and NPS accounts?",
  "response": "As an NRI (Non-Resident Indian), there are specific rules and regulations regarding various financial accounts in India. Here\u2019s what generally happens with your accounts:\n\n1. **Savings Account**:\n   - When you change your status to NRI, you cannot continue to operate a resident savings account. You are required to convert your resident savings account to an NRO (Non-Resident Ordinary) account. This is mandated by the Foreign Exchange Management Act (FEMA).\n   - An NRO account can be used to manage your income earned in India, such as rent, dividends, etc.\n\n2. **Public Provident Fund (PPF)**:\n   - NRIs are not allowed to open a new PPF account. However, if you already have a PPF account before becoming an NRI, you can continue to maintain it until its maturity. Deposit rules and benefits remain the same.\n   - NRIs are generally allowed to make contributions to existing PPF accounts, but tax benefits may differ based on your residential status.\n\n3. **National Pension System (NPS)**:\n   - NRIs are allowed to invest in NPS and continue their existing NPS accounts without any restrictions.\n   - The terms and benefits of the NPS account remain the same for NRIs, and they can continue their contributions towards retirement savings.\n\nIt\u2019s advisable to inform your bank and other financial institutions of your change in residential status and update your accounts accordingly. Consulting with a financial advisor or tax expert would also be beneficial to ensure compliance with current regulations and to optimize your investments and savings strategy.",
